.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private \- Bitcoin private keys
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private;
\&
\&        # get Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Public instance from private key
\&
\&        my $pub = $priv\->get_public_key();
\&
\&        # automatically sign standard transactions
\&
\&        $priv\->sign_transaction($tx, signing_index => $n);
\&
\&        # create signature for custom message (hash256)
\&
\&        my $sig = $priv\->sign_message(\*(AqHello world\*(Aq);
\&
\&        # signature is returned as byte string
\&        # use to_format to get the representation you need
\&
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Util::Internal qw(to_format);
\&        my $sig_hex = to_format [hex => $sig];
\&
\&        # signature verification
\&
\&        $priv\->verify_message(\*(AqHello world\*(Aq, $sig);
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class allows you to create a private key instance.
.PP
You can use a private key to get public keys and sign or verify transactions.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
\fIcompressed\fR
.IX Subsection "compressed"
.PP
Boolean value indicating if this ECC key should be compressed. Default: \f(CW\*(C`true\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_compressed\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fInetwork\fR
.IX Subsection "network"
.PP
Instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Network \- current network for this key. Can be
coerced from network id. Default: current default network.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_network\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIpurpose\fR
.IX Subsection "purpose"
.PP
BIP44 purpose which was used to obtain this key. Filled automatically when
deriving an extended key. If the key was not obtained through BIP44 derivation,
this attribute is \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_purpose\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIclearer:\fR \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fItaproot_output\fR
.IX Subsection "taproot_output"
.PP
Boolean value indicating if this key was obtained through taproot tweaking or
should be used with Schnorr signatures. Default: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_taproot_output\*(C'\fR
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
Constructor is reserved for internal and advanced use only. Use "from_serialized"
or "from_wif" instead.
.PP
\fIfrom_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "from_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $key_object = $class\->from_serialized($serialized)
.Ve
.PP
This creates a new key from string data. Argument \f(CW$serialized\fR is a
formatable bytestring containing the private key entropy.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.PP
Returns a new key object instance.
.PP
\fIto_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "to_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $serialized = $key_object\->to_serialized()
.Ve
.PP
This returns a private key as a sequence of bytes. The result is a bytestring
which can be further formated with \f(CW\*(C`to_format\*(C'\fR utility.
.PP
\fIfrom_wif\fR
.IX Subsection "from_wif"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $key_object = $class\->from_wif($wif, $network = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Creates a new private key from Wallet Import Format string.
.PP
Takes an additional optional argument, which is network name. It may be useful
if you use many networks and some have the same WIF byte.
.PP
This method will change compression and network states of the created private
key, as this data is included in WIF format.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.PP
Returns class instance.
.PP
\fIto_wif\fR
.IX Subsection "to_wif"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $wif_string = $object\->to_wif()
.Ve
.PP
Does the opposite of from_wif on a target object
.PP
\fIget_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "get_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key_object = $object\->get_public_key()
.Ve
.PP
Returns instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Public generated from the private
key.
.PP
\fIget_taproot_output_key\fR
.IX Subsection "get_taproot_output_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $prv = $object\->get_taproot_output_key($tweak_suffix = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Returns a new private key instance that represents an output taproot key, or
this key if it is marked as "taproot_output". Optional \f(CW$tweak_suffix\fR can
be passed as bytestring.
.PP
\fIsign_message\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_message"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $object\->sign_message($message)
.Ve
.PP
Signs a digest of \f(CW$message\fR (digesting it with double sha256) with a private
key.
.PP
Returns a byte string containing signature.
.PP
Character encoding note: \f(CW$message\fR should be encoded in the proper encoding
before passing it to this method. Passing Unicode string will cause the
function to fail. You can encode like this (for UTF\-8):
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        use Encode qw(encode);
\&        $message = encode(\*(AqUTF\-8\*(Aq, $message);
.Ve
.PP
\fIsign_transaction\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_transaction"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object\->sign_transaction($tx, %params)
.Ve
.PP
Signs the transaction \f(CW$tx\fR using this private key. This automatic signing
only works for standard script types, if your script is non\-standard then you
will have to sign manually.
.PP
For taproot, this signs using key path spending. Spending with script path
needs a custom solution using "sign_message". \f(CW\*(C`script_tree\*(C'\fR parameter can be
passed if taproot output had a script path.
.PP
Note that the module will let you sign any transaction with any private key.
You have to manually run "verify" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction to ensure you
used the right private key and the signature is correct for the corresponding
locking script.
.PP
Returns nothing \- the result of the function is the modification of transaction
\&\f(CW$tx\fR.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can contain:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`signing_index\*(C'\fR
.Sp
This non\-negative integer is the index of the input being signed. Required.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`redeem_script\*(C'\fR
.Sp
A Bitcoin::Crypto::Script instance or something which can be turned into a
script, used for specifying a payout script when redeeming P2SH and P2WSH
outputs.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`multisig\*(C'\fR
.Sp
A representation of the multisig signing stage. It is an array reference with
exactly two elements. The first element is the number (1\-based, not the index!)
of the currently signed multisig. The second element is the total number of
signatures required for the multisig. For example, signing 2\-out\-of\-3 multisig
can look like this (taken from \f(CW\*(C`ex/tx/multisig_redeem.pl\*(C'\fR example):
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&        # sign using the private key belonging to the first pubkey
\&        btc_prv\->from_wif(\*(AqcScAuqNfiNR7mq61QGW3LtokKAwzBzs4rbCz4Uff1NA15ysEij2i\*(Aq)
\&                \->sign_transaction($tx, signing_index => 0, redeem_script => $redeem_script, multisig => [1, 2]);
\&
\&        # sign using the private key belonging to the third pubkey
\&        btc_prv\->from_wif(\*(AqcQsSKWrBLXNY1oSZbLcJf4HF5vnKGgKko533LnkTmqRdS9Fx4SGH\*(Aq)
\&                \->sign_transaction($tx, signing_index => 0, redeem_script => $redeem_script, multisig => [2, 2]);
.Ve
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`sighash\*(C'\fR
.Sp
The sighash which should be used for the signature. By default "SIGHASH_ALL" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants
is used for pre\-taproot outputs and "SIGHASH_DEFAULT" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants for taproot
outputs.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`script_tree\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Tree instance for use in taproot. Same script tree
must be passed as used in generation of the address to correctly tweak the key.
If the key was already tweaked ("get_taproot_output_key"), this parameter can
be skipped, as no double\-tweaking will happen.
.PP
\fIverify_message\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_message"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature_valid = $object\->verify_message($message, $signature, %params)
.Ve
.PP
Verifies \f(CW$signature\fR against digest of \f(CW$message\fR (digesting it with double
sha256) using private key.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`flags\*(C'\fR
.Sp
An instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags. If not passed, full set
of consensus flags will be assumed (same as calling
"new" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags with no arguments).
.PP
Returns boolean.
.PP
Character encoding note: \f(CW$message\fR should be encoded in the proper encoding
before passing it to this method. Passing Unicode string will cause the
function to fail. You can encode like this (for UTF\-8):
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        use Encode qw(encode);
\&        $message = encode(\*(AqUTF\-8\*(Aq, $message);
.Ve
